It's same as a Japanese Biwa. It's precisely a Korean instrument that originated from Chinese Pipa as the original description said.
The unexplained removal of the accurately sourced information. Consult [[Wikipedia:Content_removal]]
The record shows that Choi Ri was the king of Nakrang. The fact that Nakrang belonged to Lelang is also disputed. Finally, Choi Ri was certainly not a squid farmer as whoever wrote it.

I've tried to see if the cited sources specifically mentioned that the sheet form of gim was introduced from Japan to Korea, but couldn't find any relevant statement. Again, these sources are used in the "Nori" article to merely support that nori's sheet form was invented in Japan during Edo period, and has no info specifically proving how nori's sheet form was introduced to gim.

I've noticed that the sources used to claim sheet form of gim was introduced from Japan to Korea in Edo period were the sources copied from "Nori" article to support that sheet form of nori was invented in Japan. Nori and gim are different foods with separate histories. The invention of nori's sheet form in Japan is not related at all to the sheet form of gim which have historically developed separately.
Can't find any statement from the cited sources that gim was introduced to Korea. Perhaps, provide the quote or page number.
